Package neureka.backend.api.template.algorithms

Class AbstractFunDeviceAlgorithm<C extends DeviceAlgorithm<C>>

java.lang.Object
neureka.backend.api.template.algorithms.AbstractDeviceAlgorithm<C>
neureka.backend.api.template.algorithms.AbstractFunDeviceAlgorithm<C>
Type Parameters:
C - The final type extending this class.
All Implemented Interfaces:
Algorithm, DeviceAlgorithm<C>, ADSupportPredicate, Execution, ExecutionPreparation, SuitabilityPredicate
Direct Known Subclasses:
BiElementwise, BiScalarBroadcast, Broadcast, DotProductAlgorithm, ElementwiseAlgorithm, FunDeviceAlgorithm, MatMulAlgorithm, NDConvolution, ScalarAlgorithm, ScalarBroadcast, SumAlgorithm
public abstract class AbstractFunDeviceAlgorithm<C extends DeviceAlgorithm<C>> extends AbstractDeviceAlgorithm<C> implements ExecutionPreparation
This is the base class for implementations of the Algorithm interface. The class implements a basic component system, as is implicitly expected by said interface. Additionally, it contains useful methods used to process passed arguments of ExecutionCall as well as an implementation of the Algorithm interface which allows its methods to be implemented in a functional programming style, meaning that instances of concrete implementations extending this abstract class have setters for lambdas representing the Algorithm methods. It is being used by the standard backend of Neureka as abstract base class for various algorithms. Conceptually an implementation of the Algorithm interface represents "a sub-kind of operation" for an instance of an implementation of the Operation interface.
The "+" operator for example has different Algorithm instances tailored to specific requirements originating from different ExecutionCall instances with unique arguments. Tensor instances within an execution call having the same shape would cause the Operation instance to choose an Algorithm instance which is responsible for performing element-wise operations, whereas otherwise the Broadcast algorithm might be called to perform the operation.

    • setCallPreparation

      public final AbstractFunDeviceAlgorithm<C> setCallPreparation(ExecutionPreparation instantiateNewTensorsForExecutionIn)
      An Algorithm will produce a Result when executing an ExecutionCall. This result must be created somehow. A ExecutionPreparation implementation instance will do just that... Often times the first entry in the array of tensors stored inside the call will be null to serve as a position for the output to be placed at. The creation of this output tensor is of course highly dependent on the type of operation and algorithm that is currently being used. Element-wise operations for example will require the creation of an output tensor with the shape of the provided input tensors, whereas the execution of a linear operation like for example a broadcast operation will require a very different approach... The lambda passed to this will be called by the prepare(ExecutionCall) method by any given Operation instances this algorithm belongs to.
      Parameters:
      instantiateNewTensorsForExecutionIn - A lambda which prepares the provided execution call (usually output instantiation).
      Returns:
      This very instance to enable method chaining.
